meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Moha","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Ukrainian and Rusyn <b>Mukha</b> and its Polish cognate   Mucha   ‘fly’.","Slovenian: nickname for an annoying or difficult person, especially someone who kept changing his mind, from <i>muha</i> ‘fly’.","Albanian: from <i>Muhë</i> (definite form <i>Muha</i>), a short form of the Albanian Muslim personal name <i>Muhamet</i> (see   Muhammad  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mucha","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Alojzy, Andrzej, Boleslaw, Eugeniusz, Grazyna, Iwan, Janina, Jerzy, Jozef, Mariusz, Miroslaw.","Polish, Czech, Slovak, and Sorbian: nickname from Polish, Slovak, Sorbian and dialect Czech <i>mucha</i> ‘fly’, denoting an irritating person or someone considered to be of no importance. Compare   Muha  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of <b>Mukha</b>: nickname from <i>mukha</i> ‘fly’ (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Muhic","meanings":["Slovenian (<b>Muhič</b>): patronymic from the nickname   Muha   ‘fly’.","Slovenian (<b>Muhič</b>): topographic name from <i>muhič</i>, a dialect name for foxtail grass (Setaria), etymologically related to <i>muha</i> ‘fly’ (compare 1 above).","Bosniak (<b>Muhić</b>): patronymic from the Bosniak Muslim personal name <i>Muho</i>, a short form of <i>Muhamed</i> (see   Muhammad  )."]},{"name":"Mosca","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Salvatore, Angelo, Domenic, Guido, Luca, Oreste, Rocco, Alfonse, Berardino, Carlo.","Italian, Portuguese, and Spanish: nickname from Italian, Portuguese, and Spanish <i>mosca</i> ‘fly’ (from Latin <i>musca</i>), possibly denoting an annoying, importunate person.","In some cases also an Italianized form (translation into Italian) of Slovenian   Muha  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Mädchen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Mason  , from the Middle English form <i>machun</i> (derived from Old French <i>machun</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mason","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which originated in the early Middle Ages as an occupational name for a worker in stone, Old French <i>maçon</i> (of Germanic origin, connected with Old English <i>macian</i> ‘to make’)."]},{"name":"Machin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Juan, Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Mario, Miguel, Pedro, Blanca, Diego, Luis, Ramon.","English: variant of   Machen  . This is the more common form of the name in Britain and Ireland.","Spanish (<b>Machín</b>): probably a nickname from <i>machín</i> ‘boor, lout’, often applied to a blacksmith's apprentice."]},{"name":"Meacham","meanings":["English: variant of   Machen  . It may occasionally also be a variant of <b>Measham</b>, a habitational name from Measham in Leicestershire. The place takes its name from the river Mease (from Old English <i>mēos</i> ‘marsh, bog’) + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mädchen von Moha was born about 1025, in France. She married Heinrich I. von Dagsburg about 1049. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"UM 1025–":"umbes 1025–Surnud","1018–1065":"1018–1065","1045–1098":"1045–1098","1051–1089":"1051–1089","1054–1098":"1054–1098","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","1018":"1018","UM 1051":"umbes 1051","1025":"1025","1089":"1089","1045":"1045","1054":"1054","1098":"1098","1065":"1065","UM 1025":"umbes 1025","um 1045":"umbes 1045","UM 1049":"umbes 1049","1051":"1051","Of, Eguish